<span class="displaytext"><center><b>"their presidential nominee even admits it. he says the high price of gas isn't the problem. the problem, he says, is that prices went up too quickly." -- senator mitch mcconnell</b></center><p>senator mitch mcconnell<br/> washington, d.c.<br/> june 12, 2008</p><p>senator mitch mcconnell: "their presidential nominee even admits it. he says the high price of gas isn't the problem. the problem, he says, is that prices went up too quickly. if he had his way, he would have raised prices but much more slowly. he would have preferred that gas prices go up much more slowly than the $1 increase we've seen under this new (PARTY NAME) congress over the past year. he would have preferred they go up more slowly than the astonishing $1.73 increase per gallon of gasoline we've seen in just the 17 months since (PARTY NAME) took over congress in january 2007. as the (PARTY NAME) nominee put it in an interview earlier this week, he would have preferred a gradual adjustment in gas prices, presumably so americans wouldn't notice the shock of it all. </p><p>"we used to think $4-a-gallon gasoline was simply unthinkable. our friends on the other side were apparently thinking about it all along. i think i would have preferred a gradual readjustment, said the (PARTY NAME) nominee."</p><p><b><i><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odok4qoybk8">watch</a> senator mcconnell </i></b></p><p><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gehaf7_tbas">watch</a> (candidate full)'s "gradual adjustment" comment</p></span>



